# Environment Variables - Interview Prep API
# ==========================================
#
# CONCEPT: Environment variables for configuration
# - Never hardcode configuration in code
# - Different values for dev/staging/prod
# - Keep secrets out of version control
#
# USAGE:
# 1. Copy this file to .env: cp .env.example .env
# 2. Update values as needed
# 3. .env is loaded automatically by docker-compose
# 4. In code: os.getenv("VARIABLE_NAME", "default_value")
#
# INTERVIEW TIP: Configuration management
# - Dev: .env file (local development)
# - Staging/Prod: Environment variables from orchestrator
#   * Kubernetes: ConfigMaps and Secrets
#   * AWS: Systems Manager Parameter Store, Secrets Manager
#   * Docker: docker run -e VAR=value
#

# ============================================================================
# REDIS CONFIGURATION
# ============================================================================

# Redis host (service name in Docker Compose / Kubernetes)
REDIS_HOST=redis

# Redis port (default: 6379)
REDIS_PORT=6379

# Redis database number (0-15, default: 0)
REDIS_DB=0

# Redis password (if authentication is enabled)
# REDIS_PASSWORD=your-secret-password

# ============================================================================
# APPLICATION CONFIGURATION
# ============================================================================

# Environment (development, staging, production)
ENVIRONMENT=development

# Log level (DEBUG, INFO, WARNING, ERROR, CRITICAL)
LOG_LEVEL=INFO

# API host (usually 0.0.0.0 to listen on all interfaces)
API_HOST=0.0.0.0

# API port
API_PORT=8000

# ============================================================================
# OPTIONAL: PRODUCTION SETTINGS
# ============================================================================

# Uncomment for production use

# Database URL (if adding database)
# DATABASE_URL=postgresql://user:password@host:5432/dbname

# Secret key for JWT tokens (if adding authentication)
# SECRET_KEY=your-super-secret-key-change-this-in-production

# CORS allowed origins (comma-separated)
# CORS_ORIGINS=https://example.com,https://www.example.com

# Sentry DSN (for error tracking)
# SENTRY_DSN=https://xxxxx@sentry.io/xxxxx

# AWS Region (if using AWS services)
# AWS_REGION=us-east-1

# ============================================================================
# DEVELOPMENT OVERRIDES
# ============================================================================

# For local development without Docker
# REDIS_HOST=localhost
# REDIS_PORT=6379

# ============================================================================
# INTERVIEW TALKING POINTS
# ============================================================================
#
# Q: Why use environment variables?
# A: Separation of config from code. Same codebase runs in dev/staging/prod
#    with different configs. Keeps secrets out of version control.
#
# Q: How do you manage secrets in production?
# A: Never in .env files or code. Use:
#    - Kubernetes Secrets
#    - AWS Secrets Manager / Systems Manager Parameter Store
#    - HashiCorp Vault
#    - Cloud provider secret management
#
# Q: What about .env files in Git?
# A: NEVER commit .env files! They contain secrets.
#    Commit .env.example (template with no real values)
#    Add .env to .gitignore
#
# Q: How to validate environment variables?
# A: Use Pydantic Settings:
#
#    from pydantic_settings import BaseSettings
#
#    class Settings(BaseSettings):
#        redis_host: str
#        redis_port: int = 6379
#        log_level: str = "INFO"
#
#        class Config:
#            env_file = ".env"
#
#    settings = Settings()
#
# ============================================================================
